description:
src/lib/server/wallets/multisig.ts:249-252:

    multisigTestAddress({
        threshold: params.threshold,
        keys: params.keys.map((k) => ({ xpub: k.xpub, fingerprint: k.fingerprint, path: k.path }))
    });

This object has no `scriptType` field. multisigScriptType() (bitcoin/multisig.ts:221-228) defaults an absent scriptType to 'p2wsh'. So regardless of what params.scriptType the user actually chose (p2sh-p2wsh or p2sh are both selectable — see MULTISIG_SCRIPT_TYPES), the "cryptographic validation... deriving the first address exercises threshold bounds, xpub parsing, and duplicate detection" comment is misleading: the derivation exercised is always the p2wsh code path, never the p2sh/p2sh-p2wsh path the wallet will actually use.

Practically this mostly only weakens the sanity-check's coverage (the underlying key resolution — xpub parse, duplicate check, threshold bounds — is script-type-independent so it doesn't silently corrupt data), but it means a bug specific to the p2sh or p2sh-p2wsh script-building code would NOT be caught by this validation gate at creation time, only later when the user actually tries to derive/display an address.

Fix: pass `scriptType: params.scriptType ?? 'p2wsh'` into the multisigTestAddress() call at multisig.ts:249 so the sanity check exercises the real script type.
